<TITLE> Bomb hits Shia procession in Pakistan </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KARACHI, Dec 28,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A bomb exploded at a Shia Muslim procession in Pakistan's commercial capital Karachi on Monday causing some casualties, police said, the latest in a series of attacks across the country that have killed hundreds. The blast underscored security challenges facing US ally Pakistan, which is struggling against al Qaeda-linked militants and is under US pressure to help stabilise neighbouring Afghanistan, where a Taliban insurgency is raging. The bomb exploded at the end of a procession for Ashura, the Shia calendar's biggest event. "We are trying to ascertain whether it was a time bomb or a suicide attack, but it is a terrorist attack," senior police official Abdul Wahid Khan told Reuters from the site, adding at least several people had been wounded. Television pictures showed a big cloud of smoke over the scene and television reporters said angry worshippers attacked a media vehicle. Processions by minority Shia Muslims are often attacked by majority Sunni Muslim milita
